A former Nigerian ambassador, Ejeviome Otobo, is dead. Otobo was last seen in Tuckahoe, New York, on June 15. The Tuckahoe police department on June 19 announced in a Facebook post that Otobo was missing and requested information from the public. A few days after, the police announced that Otobo had been found dead and sent condolences to his family. He was 70 at the time of his death. “The Tuckahoe police department regrets to inform members of the community that Ejeviome Otobo was located yesterday afternoon and is deceased,” the statement read.   22 youths found dead in South African tavern     23 killed attempting to cross from Morocco to the Spanish…     UN chief expresses shock over reports of massacres in Mali   “We would like to thank those of you who offered tips and tried to assist with the investigation. Our thoughts go out to the Otobo family during this difficult time.” Between December 2006 to October 2013, Otobo held the positions of director and deputy head of the Peace-building Support Office at the UN’s New York headquarters. From February to August 2009, Otobo acted as the assistant secretary-general at the UN. At the Global Governance Institute in Brussels, Belgium, he held the position of non-resident senior fellow in Peace-building and Global Economic Policy up until his passing.